Project Problem Statement - FMST Problem Statement: Concrete Strength Prediction

Objective

To predict the concrete strength using the data available in file "concrete.csv". Apply feature engineering and model tuning to obtain 85% to 95% accuracy.

Resources Available

The data for this project is available in file https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/concrete/compressive/. The same has been shared along with the course content.

Steps and Tasks:

Exploratory Data Quality Report Reflecting the Following:¶

Univariate analysis(10 marks)¶

Data types and description of the independent attributes which should include (name, range of values observed, central values (mean and median), standard deviation and quartiles, analysis of the body of distributions/tails, missing values, outliers, duplicates(10 Marks)

Bi-variate analysis(10 marks)¶

between the predictor variables and between the predictor variables and target column. Comment on your findings in terms of their relationship and degree of relation if any. Visualize the analysis using boxplots and pair plots, histograms, or density curves.

Feature Engineering techniques(10 marks)¶

  1. Identify opportunities (if any) to extract new features from existing features, drop a feature(if required) Hint: Feature Extraction, for example, consider a dataset with two features length and breadth. From this, we can extract a new feature Area which would be length * breadth.

  2. Get the data model ready and do a train test split.

  3. Decide on the complexity of the model, should it be a simple linear model in terms of parameters or would a quadratic or higher degree.

Creating the Model and Tuning It:(30 marks)¶

  1. Algorithms that you think will be suitable for this project. Use Kfold Cross-Validation to evaluate model performance. Use appropriate metrics and make a DataFrame to compare models w.r.t their metrics. (at least 3 algorithms, one bagging and one boosting based algorithms have to be there). (15 marks)
  1. Techniques employed to squeeze that extra performance out of the model without making it overfit. Use Grid Search or Random Search on any of the two models used above. Make a DataFrame to compare models after hyperparameter tuning and their metrics as above. (15 marks)

Attribute Information:

Given are the variable name, variable type, the measurement unit, and a brief description. The concrete compressive strength is the regression problem. The order of this listing corresponds to the order of numerals along the rows of the database.

Name Data Type Measurement Description

  1. Cement (cement) quantitative kg in a m3 mixture Input Variable
  2. Blast Furnace Slag (slag) quantitative kg in a m3 mixture Input Variable
  3. Fly Ash (ash) quantitative kg in a m3 mixture Input Variable
  4. Water(water) quantitative kg in a m3 mixture Input Variable
  5. Superplasticizer (superplastic) quantitative kg in a m3 mixture Input Variable
  6. Coarse Aggregate (coarseagg) quantitative kg in a m3 mixture Input Variable
  7. Fine Aggregate (fineagg) quantitative kg in a m3 mixture Input Variable
  8. Age(age) quantitative Day (1~365) Input Variable
  9. Concrete compressive strength(strength) quantitative MPa Output Variable

Outcome:¶
  1. We can observe from the above data analys that there are some 0 values in slag, ash and superplastic columns. So we can treat those 0 values by imputing with mean alues.
In [9]:
#replacing the 0 values with their mean value
df1_concrete["slag"] = df1_concrete.slag.replace(to_replace = 0, value = df1_concrete.slag.mean())
df1_concrete["ash"] = df1_concrete.ash.replace(to_replace = 0, value = df1_concrete.ash.mean())
df1_concrete["superplastic"] = df1_concrete.superplastic.replace(to_replace = 0, value = df1_concrete.superplastic.mean())

In [11]:
#Calculation of outliers in each column
q1 = df1_concrete.quantile(0.25)
q3 = df1_concrete.quantile(0.75)
IQR = q3 - q1
outlier = ((df1_concrete.iloc[:] < (q1 - 1.5 * IQR)) | (df1_concrete.iloc[:] > (q3 + 1.5 * IQR))).sum(axis = 0)
outlier_df = pd.DataFrame(outlier, index = df1_concrete.columns, columns = ["Number of Outliers"])
outlier_df["Outliers in %"] = round(outlier_df["Number of Outliers"] * 100 / len(df1_concrete), 2)
outlier_df

In [25]:
#Linear Regression
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score

model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_predict = model.predict(X_test)

RMSE_lr = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_predict))
r2_lr = r2_score(y_test, y_predict)
print(RMSE_lr)
print(r2_lr)

0.6240968977684398
0.6268686735706244
In [26]:
#Polynomial linear regression of degree 2 (quadratic)
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures

polynomial_features2 = PolynomialFeatures(2)

X_train_polynom = polynomial_features2.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_polynom = polynomial_features2.fit_transform(X_test)

model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X_train_polynom, y_train)
y_poly_predict = model.predict(X_test_polynom)

RMSE_pl2 = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_poly_predict))
r2_pl2 = r2_score(y_test, y_poly_predict)
print(RMSE_pl2)
print(r2_pl2)

0.503212559513482
0.7574168627646298
In [27]:
#Polynomial linear regression of degree 3 (cubic)
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures

polynomial_features3 = PolynomialFeatures(3)

X_train_polynom = polynomial_features3.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_polynom = polynomial_features3.fit_transform(X_test)

model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X_train_polynom, y_train)
y_poly_predict = model.predict(X_test_polynom)

RMSE_pl3 = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_poly_predict))
r2_pl3 = r2_score(y_test, y_poly_predict)

print(RMSE_pl3)
print(r2_pl3)

0.412709778475555
0.8368274193601339
Conclusions¶
  1. From the above calculations of linear regression vs polynomial regression, it is quite clear that polynomial regregression able to fit the data better than the linear regression
  2. RMSE has decreased and r2-score has increased as compared to the linear regression.
  3. Polynomial regression of degree 3(cubic) fits better than that of degree 2 (quadratic). But if we further increase the degree the model will become overfit.
